Hi YPA Partners,
 
This is a reminder email that Dec 3 is fast approaching for Milestone 2 of this security update.  Please see below.

**********************************************************************************************************************************
An upcoming security patch is planned for the Yahoo Partner Ads (YPA) platform. Please read as we’ve noted from our configuration records, that one or more of your implementations is serving CSS from a domain that is not within your site group, or has been identified as a public CDN.

On Monday, December 3 at 19:00 UTC, YPA will no longer serve custom CSS from domains that are not owned by approved YPA publishers. We are rolling out a critical security update to prevent cross-site-scripting attacks via unauthorized/uncontrolled code.

This impacts YPA partners who: 

Use custom CSS that is hosted on a domain that is not specified in one of the publisher's Site
Groups. For example, any files hosted on Content Delivery Networks (CDNs) such as AWS,
Akamai, CloudFlare, etc. This may also include partner-owned domains that are not part of public YPA implementations (e.g. partner-XYZ-file-hosting.com).

What do I need to do?

If you are using custom CSS within your YPA implementation, move your CSS to a domain that you own and that is specified within your site group in the YPA administration interface. For security purposes, we do not allow hosting from public CDNs (such as AWS, Cloudflare, Fastly, etc.), nor do we allow CDNs to be added to site groups.

From: DDC Accounts [mailto:ddcaccounts@ddc.com] 
Sent: Thursday, November 1, 2018 2:11 PM
Cc: DDC Accounts <ddcaccounts@ddc.com>
Subject: YPA security update regarding CSS
Importance: High
 
Hi YPA Partners,
 
We just got the following email from Oath.  Please read below to see if this applies to your sites.
 
**********************************************************************************************************************************
 
IMPORTANT SECURITY UPDATE FOR YPA PARTNERS

An upcoming security patch is planned for the Yahoo Partner Ads (YPA) platform. Please read to see if this affects your implementation, as some configurations may need to be updated. 

The patch limits the domains on which custom CSS can be hosted, and will ensure that CSS cannot be used for malicious or destructive purposes (including XSS, or cross-site scripting attacks) by unknown or untrusted third parties. 

This impacts YPA partners who: 
Use custom CSS that is hosted on a domain that is not specified in one of the publisher's Site Groups. For example, any files hosted on Content Delivery Networks (CDNs) such as AWS, Akamai, CloudFlare, etc. This may also include partner-owned domains that are not part of public YPA implementations (e.g. partner-XYZ-file-hosting.com).
This DOES NOT impact partners who:
Are not currently using custom CSS
Are using custom CSS that is hosted on a domain that is part of one of the publisher's Site Groups (as specified in the YPA administrative portal)
Host CSS on a subdomain of one of their Site Group domains (e.g. https://files.publisherXYZ.com/ypa.css for the implementation publisherXYZ.com)
FAQ:
 
This affects one or more of my YPA implementations. What do I need to do?

You simply need to move your custom CSS to the  APPROVED domain -- this can be any domain within your site group, and is not restricted to the domain on which you're serving YPA. You'll then need to update your ad configs accordingly, either via the YPA administrative UI via DDC, or within the Javascript ad tag. 

There are two milestones for this update:

Milestone 1: Wednesday, November 7 starting at 12:00 PM PST (19:00 UTC): publisher CSS files must be hosted on publisher-owned domains, as specified in the Site Groups within the partnerads.yahoo.com administrative portal. We will not allow files to be hosted on CDNs. 

This is a very short deadline, so to ensure that existing YPA implementations will not break, and to give publishers extra time to migrate their CSS, we will temporarily whitelist any full CSS URLs that has been used in the past month. Any new CSS files will need to be added to one of the publisher domains in any Site Group. In addition, any changes to file URLs (including cache-busting or other URL parameters) will require a new file to be hosted on a Site Group domain.  

Milestone 2: Monday, December 3 at 12:00 PM PST (19:00 UTC): The temporary whitelist will be removed, and all custom CSS will be required to be hosted on a publisher-owned domain.  

We apologize for the short notice, but appreciate all efforts to help us ensure the security of the platform for all users. 
 
**********************************************************************************************************************************
 
Thank you,
